    <questiontext format="markdown">
      <text><![CDATA[**32.4  E3 Crank-Nicolson Scheme**

The temperature \\\(u(x, t)\\\) of a metal bar of length \\\(ℓ = {@L@}\\\) at a distance \\\(x\\\) from one end and at
time \\\(t\\\) is modelled by the partial diﬀerential equation

\\\(u_t = \alpha u_{xx}\quad (0 < x < \ell, t > 0)\\\)

It is given that the metal has diﬀusivity {@'alpha=alpha@}, that the two ends of the bar are kept at temperature \\\(u = 0\\\) and that the initial temperature distribution is \\\(u(x, 0) = f(x) = x(\ell − x)\\\).

Use the Crank-Nicolson scheme with \\\(\delta x = {@dx@}\\\) and \\\(\delta t = {@dt@}\\\) to approximate \\\(u(x, t)\\\) at
\\\(t = \delta t\\\) and \\\(t = 2\delta t\\\). 

\\\(r=\alpha \delta t / (\delta x)^2=\\\) [[input:S_r]] [[validation:S_r]] [[feedback:r]]

Grid point values at \\\(t=\delta t\\\) with at least 3 s.f.
[[input:S_u1]] [[validation:S_u1]] [[feedback:u1]]

Grid point values at \\\(t=2\delta t\\\) with at least 3 s.f.
[[input:S_u2]] [[validation:S_u2]] [[feedback:u2]]]]></text>
